Why the SVD Rules¶

SVD = Singular Value Decomposition

\[ M = U D V^{T} \]

The SVD is the archetypal matrix factorization

Why should you care that you can write 1 matrix in terms of 3 matrices?

Because the SVD is the perfect summary of a matrix

What does it mean to summarize a matrix?

Simpler: what does it mean to summarize a vector?

What does it mean to take the mean of a vector?

In [174]:
v = [1, 2, 10]
Out[174]:
3-element Int64 Array:
  1
  2
 10
In [175]:
mean(v)
Out[175]:
4.333333333333333
In [176]:
sum(v) / length(v)
Out[176]:
4.333333333333333

We all know how to compute means

But why do means matter to us?

The mean is a good summary of a vector

In [182]:
function curve(f::Function; from::Real = 0.0, to::Real = 1.0, N::Integer = 1_024)
      x = [from:((to - from) / (N - 1)):to]
      y = [f(x_i) for x_i in x]
      plot(x = x, y = y, kind = :line)
end

The mean minimizes the sum of squared errors, E(s)



    

    




The SVD does something similar

Why is this ability to summarize matrices the CS equivalent of being born on Krypton?



    

    




Because the SVD gives you a tool to extract only the important structure from a matrix



    

    




What sorts of things can be described using matrices?



    

    




    

  • Social networks
    • 

  • Text corpora
    • 

  • Stock prices
    • 

  • Voting records
    • 




    

    



  
Social Network Analysis¶





    

    




Let's show how we can use the SVD to make sense of social networks

The U matrix from the SVD gives us one representation of the social graph



    

    




Entries that are similar in U are also similar in the social network



    

    




So we can use the columns of U to visualize a social network



    

    




We can do something similar with text documents

function makedtm(tokens::Vector, index::Dict)
    d = length(tokens)
    L = length(all_tokens)
    m = zeros(Int, d, L)
    for i in 1:d
        for token in tokens[i]
            j = index[token]
            m[i, j] += 1
        end
    end
    return m
end

What was this second approach?



    

    




We rotated the original data by the matrix V



    

    




This rotation forms the principal components of the original data



    

    




Let's see the rotation on 2D data to get a sense for it
